{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ddabe358-3295-4e91-a53f-7e99b039f185","content":"Here are the **3 performance anti-patterns** found in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Recursive wildcard glob (line 9, `EvalHeavy.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to walk the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. This is extremely expensive in large repos. Prefer narrow, targeted globs (e.g., `docs\\*.md`).\n\n---\n\n### 2. File I/O via property function (line 13, `EvalHeavy.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` during evaluation performs **disk I/O on every evaluation pass** (IDE refreshes, restores, builds). This blocks the evaluation thread. Move file reads to a build target instead.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Deeply chained import chain (`imports/`)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels of nested `<Import>` files, each importing the next. Each import adds XML parsing overhead and expands the evaluation graph. Flatten into a single `.props` file or reduce nesting depth when properties are this simple.\n\n---\n\n**Impact summary:** Issue #1 (wildcard glob) is typically the worst offender at scale—evaluation time grows with the file count in the repo. Issue #2 (file I/O) adds per-evaluation latency. Issue #3 (import depth) has modest cost here but compounds in real-world projects with larger chains.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"416e65cb-c61e-4931-949c-f47b367e0c71","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues:\n\n1. **Deep nested import chain** (level1.props → level2.props → level3.props) - 3 levels deep\n2. **Recursive wildcard glob** (`**\\*.*`) in AdditionalFiles - very expensive during evaluation\n3. **File I/O during evaluation** - `System.IO.File.ReadAllText('build-notes.txt')` property function reads a file during project evaluation\n4. **Import outside SDK imports** - The `<Import>` is placed between SDK-injected imports and ItemGroups, which can cause re-evaluation\n\n\n5. **Consolidating these findings** - The combination of nested imports, expensive glob patterns, and synchronous file reads during evaluation is creating a compounding performance bottleneck that needs to be addressed systematically.","outputTokens":590,"requestId":"1411:3ED481:1497ACE:17F9BC9:69EC1689"},"id":"67ca327f-f808-4934-bc54-e15ec8d0d6c7","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:19:20.166Z","parentId":"95c4e082-c713-4683-bd22-8e17489a6b2c"}
